    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\nHelp the `Painter` navigate through The Neighborhood to reach the traffic cone!\r\n\r\n1. Create a `Painter` object.\r\n\r\n2. Use the `move()` and `turn_left()` methods to navigate through The Neighborhood to reach the traffic cone.\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/982457a7e4c9e6efc992912c8266833f-U1L4-L4b.gif)\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nIs your code not working the way you expected? One helpful strategy finding the cause of an issue is to use `print()` to track where you're expecting the `Painter` to be and the direction they are facing. For example:\r\n\r\n```\r\nravi.move()\r\nravi.move()\r\nravi.move()\r\nprint(\"ravi is next to the traffic cone facing east\")\r\n\r\nravi.turn_left()\r\nravi.turn_left()\r\nravi.turn_left()\r\nprint(\"ravi is next to the traffic cone facing south\")\r\n```",
